<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Abies</i> <i>grandis</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the tree canopy with <i>Alnus</i> <i>rubra</i>, <i>Picea</i> <i>sitchensis</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>muricata</i>, <i>Sequoia</i> <i>sempervirens</i> and <i>Tsuga</i> <i>heterophylla</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text"> Trees < 70 m; canopy is continuous. Shrub layer is sparse to intermittent. Herbaceous layer is open to abundant. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Abies grandis</i> > 60% cover in the tree canopy (Nature-Serve 2007).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Maritime terraces, coastline slopes, and bluffs. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Abies grandis</i> as a FACU+ plant. </div>
</div>

        
